Myocardial ischaemia during daily life in patients with stable angina: its relation to symptoms and heart rate changes. In thirty patients with stable angina and positive exercise tests, ambulatory ST segment monitoring was used to record episodes of transient myocardial ischaemia during daily life. All patients had four consecutive days of monitoring and in 20 patients long-term variability was assessed by repeated 48 hour monitoring and exercise testing over 18 months. There were 1934 episodes of rectilinear or downsloping ST-depression (911, 1 mm 638, 2 mm